# Code Standards

- `<name>.go`: testable business logic.
- `<name>_init.go`: constructors, OS/filesystem setup, panic-recovery wrappers, schema init. Excluded from coverage.
- No business logic in `*_init.go`.
- Put `// nocov` on a line inside the uncovered block, and only for paths that truly cannot be tested.
- Unused parameters: remove them and update callers when you own the signature. When a shared `func`/interface forces an argument that only some implementations need, use `_` for that parameter (or omit the name: `func(string)`).
- Prefer dependency injection (interfaces) over concrete types.
- Source-package-specific structure lives in `datasources.mdc`.


## Comments

- Every function and method must have a doc comment
- The comment must be 1-2 sentences, and must not include the name
- The comment must describe:
  - what the function does
  - why it exists in the caller/system context
  - important inputs or assumptions
  - important side effects
  - return/output semantics when non-obvious
- Prefer compressed prose over keyword labels, but all of the above must be covered when relevant.
- “Returns X” or “handles Y” alone is not sufficient.
- For trivial pure helpers, inputs/outputs may be implicit if obvious, but why the helper exists must still be stated.
- When there is a tradeoff, the comment should favor caller-visible behavior over implementation detail.
